[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":1150},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fpython\u002F2021\u002F09\u002F12\u002Flearning-python-from-javascript-11-list-20-operations\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fpython\u002F2021\u002F09\u002F12\u002Flearning-python-from-javascript-11-list-20-operations\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fpython\u002F2021\u002F09\u002F12\u002Flearning-python-from-javascript-11-list-20-operations\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fpython\u002F2021\u002F09\u002F12\u002Flearning-python-from-javascript-11-list-20-operations\u002F":1127,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fpython\u002F2021\u002F09\u002F12\u002Flearning-python-from-javascript-11-list-20-operations\u002F":1136},"\u002Fpython\u002F20210912\u002F1574142266\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":1109,"date":1110,"description":1111,"extension":1112,"lang":1113,"meta":1114,"navigation":312,"path":1115,"readingMinutes":1116,"seo":1117,"standalone":1118,"stem":1119,"tags":1120,"tldr":1124,"updated":1110,"url":1125,"__hash__":1126},"content\u002Fen\u002FPython\u002Flearning-python-from-javascript-11-list-20-operations.md","Learning Python From a JS Dev's View (11): 20 Ways to Work With Lists","1002407379",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":1078},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,27,132,135,143,146,149,152,155,158,162,169,198,201,212,231,233,238,257,260,279,282,287,326,328,333,353,355,360,380,383,388,407,410,415,434,437,440,443,451,480,483,491,525,528,539,558,561,569,588,590,595,607,647,649,666,669,693,696,719,722,745,748,754,776,778,786,835,837,842,886,889,903,932,935,948,975,977,982,1010,1014,1023,1027,1030,1034,1067,1074],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"Now that we've gone over dictionaries and lists, I wanted to slip in a lighter, no-pressure chapter to walk through and jot down how list handling works in Python.",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"javascripts-20-array-methods","JavaScript's 20 array methods",[17,25,26],{},"In JavaScript we have somewhere around twenty array methods. In case you've forgotten any of them, here's a quick refresher:",[28,29,30,37,42,47,52,57,62,67,72,77,82,87,92,97,102,107,112,117,122,127],"ul",{},[31,32,33],"li",{},[34,35,36],"code",{},"shift",[31,38,39],{},[34,40,41],{},"unshift",[31,43,44],{},[34,45,46],{},"pop",[31,48,49],{},[34,50,51],{},"push",[31,53,54],{},[34,55,56],{},"splice",[31,58,59],{},[34,60,61],{},"sort",[31,63,64],{},[34,65,66],{},"reverse",[31,68,69],{},[34,70,71],{},"length",[31,73,74],{},[34,75,76],{},"join",[31,78,79],{},[34,80,81],{},"reduce",[31,83,84],{},[34,85,86],{},"reduceRight",[31,88,89],{},[34,90,91],{},"indexOf",[31,93,94],{},[34,95,96],{},"lastindexOf",[31,98,99],{},[34,100,101],{},"some",[31,103,104],{},[34,105,106],{},"every",[31,108,109],{},[34,110,111],{},"forEach",[31,113,114],{},[34,115,116],{},"map",[31,118,119],{},[34,120,121],{},"filter",[31,123,124],{},[34,125,126],{},"slice",[31,128,129],{},[34,130,131],{},"concat",[17,133,134],{},"So what about Python? Does it have a similar pile of array operations like JavaScript does? Basically, yes. And here I've tried my best to group them into two buckets:",[28,136,137,140],{},[31,138,139],{},"Methods that might affect the original list",[31,141,142],{},"Methods that won't affect the original list",[17,144,145],{},"I'll go through each one with a short explanation and an example.",[17,147,148],{},"So this one's a bit more relaxed — it's basically just getting a feel for how these operations are used. If I missed something or got something wrong here, go easy on me (there are just SO many of them~~~).",[17,150,151],{},"I did a rough count and the number I listed happens to match JavaScript exactly — twenty as well. And for this post, I won't be dropping any meme images.",[12,153,139],{"id":154},"methods-that-might-affect-the-original-list",[17,156,157],{},"Basically, the ones in this group can change the original list depending on how you use them, so you want to be a little careful here — otherwise you might end up writing a bug.",[159,160,161],"h3",{"id":161},"insert",[17,163,164,165,168],{},"This stuffs data into a specific index position. Note that the first argument is the index position and the second is the content you want to insert. Also, the position starts counting from ",[34,166,167],{},"0",".",[170,171,176],"pre",{"className":172,"code":173,"language":174,"meta":175,"style":175},"language-py shiki shiki-themes github-light github-light github-dark-high-contrast","lis = ['A', 'B', 'C']\nlis.insert(1, 'Q')\nprint(lis) # ['A', 'Q', 'B', 'C']\n","py","",[34,177,178,186,192],{"__ignoreMap":175},[179,180,183],"span",{"class":181,"line":182},"line",1,[179,184,185],{},"lis = ['A', 'B', 'C']\n",[179,187,189],{"class":181,"line":188},2,[179,190,191],{},"lis.insert(1, 'Q')\n",[179,193,195],{"class":181,"line":194},3,[179,196,197],{},"print(lis) # ['A', 'Q', 'B', 'C']\n",[159,199,200],{"id":200},"append",[17,202,203,205,206,208,209,211],{},[34,204,200],{}," is about 87% like JavaScript's ",[34,207,51],{}," method, so you can pretty much think of it as ",[34,210,51],{}," — it inserts data at the end of the list.",[170,213,215],{"className":172,"code":214,"language":174,"meta":175,"style":175},"lis = ['A', 'B', 'C']\nlis.append('Q')\nprint(lis) # ['A', 'B', 'C', Q]\n",[34,216,217,221,226],{"__ignoreMap":175},[179,218,219],{"class":181,"line":182},[179,220,185],{},[179,222,223],{"class":181,"line":188},[179,224,225],{},"lis.append('Q')\n",[179,227,228],{"class":181,"line":194},[179,229,230],{},"print(lis) # ['A', 'B', 'C', Q]\n",[159,232,46],{"id":46},[17,234,235,237],{},[34,236,46],{}," pulls the last item out of the list:",[170,239,241],{"className":172,"code":240,"language":174,"meta":175,"style":175},"lis = ['A', 'B', 'C']\nprint(lis.pop()) # C\nprint(lis) # ['A', 'B']\n",[34,242,243,247,252],{"__ignoreMap":175},[179,244,245],{"class":181,"line":182},[179,246,185],{},[179,248,249],{"class":181,"line":188},[179,250,251],{},"print(lis.pop()) # C\n",[179,253,254],{"class":181,"line":194},[179,255,256],{},"print(lis) # ['A', 'B']\n",[17,258,259],{},"But if you pass in an index position, it pulls out that specific item instead:",[170,261,263],{"className":172,"code":262,"language":174,"meta":175,"style":175},"lis = ['A', 'B', 'C']\nprint(lis.pop(1)) # B\nprint(lis) # ['A', 'C']\n",[34,264,265,269,274],{"__ignoreMap":175},[179,266,267],{"class":181,"line":182},[179,268,185],{},[179,270,271],{"class":181,"line":188},[179,272,273],{},"print(lis.pop(1)) # B\n",[179,275,276],{"class":181,"line":194},[179,277,278],{},"print(lis) # ['A', 'C']\n",[159,280,281],{"id":281},"extend",[17,283,284,286],{},[34,285,281],{}," means to expand or lengthen, so the idea is similar to adding lists together.",[170,288,290],{"className":172,"code":289,"language":174,"meta":175,"style":175},"lisA = ['A', 'B', 'C']\nlisB = ['D', 'E', 'F']\nlisA.extend(lisB)\n\nprint(lisA) # ['A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E', 'F']\nprint(lisB) # ['D', 'E', 'F']\n",[34,291,292,297,302,307,314,320],{"__ignoreMap":175},[179,293,294],{"class":181,"line":182},[179,295,296],{},"lisA = ['A', 'B', 'C']\n",[179,298,299],{"class":181,"line":188},[179,300,301],{},"lisB = ['D', 'E', 'F']\n",[179,303,304],{"class":181,"line":194},[179,305,306],{},"lisA.extend(lisB)\n",[179,308,310],{"class":181,"line":309},4,[179,311,313],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":312},true,"\n",[179,315,317],{"class":181,"line":316},5,[179,318,319],{},"print(lisA) # ['A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E', 'F']\n",[179,321,323],{"class":181,"line":322},6,[179,324,325],{},"print(lisB) # ['D', 'E', 'F']\n",[159,327,61],{"id":61},[17,329,330,332],{},[34,331,61],{}," is super simple — it just sorts the contents of the list. By default it sorts based on ASCII.",[170,334,336],{"className":172,"code":335,"language":174,"meta":175,"style":175},"lis = [14, 30, 35, 42, 5, 16, 70, 98, 19, 100]\nlis.sort()\nprint(lis) # [5, 14, 16, 19, 30, 35, 42, 70, 98, 100]\n",[34,337,338,343,348],{"__ignoreMap":175},[179,339,340],{"class":181,"line":182},[179,341,342],{},"lis = [14, 30, 35, 42, 5, 16, 70, 98, 19, 100]\n",[179,344,345],{"class":181,"line":188},[179,346,347],{},"lis.sort()\n",[179,349,350],{"class":181,"line":194},[179,351,352],{},"print(lis) # [5, 14, 16, 19, 30, 35, 42, 70, 98, 100]\n",[159,354,66],{"id":66},[17,356,357,359],{},[34,358,66],{}," shouldn't need much explanation — it just reverses the list.",[170,361,363],{"className":172,"code":362,"language":174,"meta":175,"style":175},"lis = ['A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E', 'F']\nlis.reverse()\nprint(lis) # ['F', 'E', 'D', 'C', 'B', 'A']\n",[34,364,365,370,375],{"__ignoreMap":175},[179,366,367],{"class":181,"line":182},[179,368,369],{},"lis = ['A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E', 'F']\n",[179,371,372],{"class":181,"line":188},[179,373,374],{},"lis.reverse()\n",[179,376,377],{"class":181,"line":194},[179,378,379],{},"print(lis) # ['F', 'E', 'D', 'C', 'B', 'A']\n",[159,381,382],{"id":382},"remove",[17,384,385,387],{},[34,386,382],{}," works by deleting based on the content. So if you only know what the content is but not its index position, this is the method to use.",[170,389,391],{"className":172,"code":390,"language":174,"meta":175,"style":175},"lis = ['A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E', 'F']\nlis.remove('D')\nprint(lis) # ['A', 'B', 'C', 'E', 'F']\n",[34,392,393,397,402],{"__ignoreMap":175},[179,394,395],{"class":181,"line":182},[179,396,369],{},[179,398,399],{"class":181,"line":188},[179,400,401],{},"lis.remove('D')\n",[179,403,404],{"class":181,"line":194},[179,405,406],{},"print(lis) # ['A', 'B', 'C', 'E', 'F']\n",[159,408,409],{"id":409},"clear",[17,411,412,414],{},[34,413,409],{}," is nice and blunt — it just empties the list.",[170,416,418],{"className":172,"code":417,"language":174,"meta":175,"style":175},"lis = ['A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E', 'F']\nlis.clear()\nprint(lis) # []\n",[34,419,420,424,429],{"__ignoreMap":175},[179,421,422],{"class":181,"line":182},[179,423,369],{},[179,425,426],{"class":181,"line":188},[179,427,428],{},"lis.clear()\n",[179,430,431],{"class":181,"line":194},[179,432,433],{},"print(lis) # []\n",[12,435,142],{"id":436},"methods-that-wont-affect-the-original-list",[17,438,439],{},"Next up are the operations that mostly leave the original list alone.",[159,441,442],{"id":442},"len",[17,444,445,447,448,450],{},[34,446,442],{}," is easy to grasp — it's a lot like JavaScript's ",[34,449,71],{},", and you use it to get the length of an array.",[170,452,454],{"className":172,"code":453,"language":174,"meta":175,"style":175},"lisA = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 0]\nprint(len(lisA))  # 10\n\nlisB = ['r', 'a', 'y']\nprint(len(lisB)) # 3\n",[34,455,456,461,466,470,475],{"__ignoreMap":175},[179,457,458],{"class":181,"line":182},[179,459,460],{},"lisA = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 0]\n",[179,462,463],{"class":181,"line":188},[179,464,465],{},"print(len(lisA))  # 10\n",[179,467,468],{"class":181,"line":194},[179,469,313],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":312},[179,471,472],{"class":181,"line":309},[179,473,474],{},"lisB = ['r', 'a', 'y']\n",[179,476,477],{"class":181,"line":316},[179,478,479],{},"print(len(lisB)) # 3\n",[159,481,482],{"id":482},"index",[17,484,485,486,488,489,168],{},"This finds the index position of a specific thing in the list. Note that ",[34,487,482],{}," starts from ",[34,490,167],{},[170,492,494],{"className":172,"code":493,"language":174,"meta":175,"style":175},"lis = ['r', 'a', 'y']\n\nprint(lis.index('r')) # 0\nprint(lis.index('a')) # 1\nprint(lis.index('y')) # 2\nprint(lis) # ['r', 'a', 'y']\n",[34,495,496,501,505,510,515,520],{"__ignoreMap":175},[179,497,498],{"class":181,"line":182},[179,499,500],{},"lis = ['r', 'a', 'y']\n",[179,502,503],{"class":181,"line":188},[179,504,313],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":312},[179,506,507],{"class":181,"line":194},[179,508,509],{},"print(lis.index('r')) # 0\n",[179,511,512],{"class":181,"line":309},[179,513,514],{},"print(lis.index('a')) # 1\n",[179,516,517],{"class":181,"line":316},[179,518,519],{},"print(lis.index('y')) # 2\n",[179,521,522],{"class":181,"line":322},[179,523,524],{},"print(lis) # ['r', 'a', 'y']\n",[159,526,527],{"id":527},"reversed",[17,529,530,532,533,535,536,168],{},[34,531,527],{}," is very much like ",[34,534,66],{},", except it doesn't touch the original list. So after reversing it returns a new list — just note that you need to convert it back with ",[34,537,538],{},"list",[170,540,542],{"className":172,"code":541,"language":174,"meta":175,"style":175},"lis = ['A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E', 'F']\nprint(list(reversed(lis))) # ['F', 'E', 'D', 'C', 'B', 'A']\nprint(lis) # ['A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E', 'F']\n",[34,543,544,548,553],{"__ignoreMap":175},[179,545,546],{"class":181,"line":182},[179,547,369],{},[179,549,550],{"class":181,"line":188},[179,551,552],{},"print(list(reversed(lis))) # ['F', 'E', 'D', 'C', 'B', 'A']\n",[179,554,555],{"class":181,"line":194},[179,556,557],{},"print(lis) # ['A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E', 'F']\n",[159,559,560],{"id":560},"sorted",[17,562,563,565,566,568],{},[34,564,560],{}," is very similar to ",[34,567,61],{},", except it doesn't affect the original list.",[170,570,572],{"className":172,"code":571,"language":174,"meta":175,"style":175},"lis = [14, 30, 35, 42, 5, 16, 70, 98, 19, 100]\nprint(sorted(lis)) # [5, 14, 16, 19, 30, 35, 42, 70, 98, 100]\nprint(lis) # [14, 30, 35, 42, 5, 16, 70, 98, 19, 100]\n",[34,573,574,578,583],{"__ignoreMap":175},[179,575,576],{"class":181,"line":182},[179,577,342],{},[179,579,580],{"class":181,"line":188},[179,581,582],{},"print(sorted(lis)) # [5, 14, 16, 19, 30, 35, 42, 70, 98, 100]\n",[179,584,585],{"class":181,"line":194},[179,586,587],{},"print(lis) # [14, 30, 35, 42, 5, 16, 70, 98, 19, 100]\n",[159,589,538],{"id":538},[17,591,592,594],{},[34,593,538],{}," can be used for conversion, but it can also copy out a fresh array.",[17,596,597,598,601,602,604,605,168],{},"Before we look at the example, I want to mention something first. In the example below I use a pretty special method called ",[34,599,600],{},"id()",", which returns the memory location. I bring it up here because we'll use ",[34,603,538],{}," to copy out a list, and to prove the two lists are different we'll use ",[34,606,600],{},[170,608,610],{"className":172,"code":609,"language":174,"meta":175,"style":175},"lisA = [14, 30, 35, 42, 5, 16, 70, 98, 19, 100]\nlisB = list(lisA)\nprint(id(lisA)) # 4464143936\nprint(id(lisB)) # 4464824640\n\nlisA[0] = 1\nprint(lisB) # [14, 30, 35, 42, 5, 16, 70, 98, 19, 100]\n",[34,611,612,617,622,627,632,636,641],{"__ignoreMap":175},[179,613,614],{"class":181,"line":182},[179,615,616],{},"lisA = [14, 30, 35, 42, 5, 16, 70, 98, 19, 100]\n",[179,618,619],{"class":181,"line":188},[179,620,621],{},"lisB = list(lisA)\n",[179,623,624],{"class":181,"line":194},[179,625,626],{},"print(id(lisA)) # 4464143936\n",[179,628,629],{"class":181,"line":309},[179,630,631],{},"print(id(lisB)) # 4464824640\n",[179,633,634],{"class":181,"line":316},[179,635,313],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":312},[179,637,638],{"class":181,"line":322},[179,639,640],{},"lisA[0] = 1\n",[179,642,644],{"class":181,"line":643},7,[179,645,646],{},"print(lisB) # [14, 30, 35, 42, 5, 16, 70, 98, 19, 100]\n",[159,648,126],{"id":126},[17,650,651,652,654,655,657,658,661,662,665],{},"Don't get too excited when you see ",[34,653,126],{}," — in Python, ",[34,656,126],{}," works a bit differently. You mainly use ",[34,659,660],{},"[:]"," to slice the list, rather than the ",[34,663,664],{},"slice()"," syntax.",[17,667,668],{},"Grab from index 0 up to index 4:",[170,670,672],{"className":172,"code":671,"language":174,"meta":175,"style":175},"lisA = ['A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E', 'F']\nlisB = lisA[:4]\nprint(lisA) # ['A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E', 'F']\nprint(lisB) # ['A', 'B', 'C', 'D']\n",[34,673,674,679,684,688],{"__ignoreMap":175},[179,675,676],{"class":181,"line":182},[179,677,678],{},"lisA = ['A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E', 'F']\n",[179,680,681],{"class":181,"line":188},[179,682,683],{},"lisB = lisA[:4]\n",[179,685,686],{"class":181,"line":194},[179,687,319],{},[179,689,690],{"class":181,"line":309},[179,691,692],{},"print(lisB) # ['A', 'B', 'C', 'D']\n",[17,694,695],{},"Grab from index 2 up to index 4:",[170,697,699],{"className":172,"code":698,"language":174,"meta":175,"style":175},"lisA = ['A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E', 'F']\nlisB = lisA[2:4]\nprint(lisA) # ['A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E', 'F']\nprint(lisB) # ['C', 'D']\n",[34,700,701,705,710,714],{"__ignoreMap":175},[179,702,703],{"class":181,"line":182},[179,704,678],{},[179,706,707],{"class":181,"line":188},[179,708,709],{},"lisB = lisA[2:4]\n",[179,711,712],{"class":181,"line":194},[179,713,319],{},[179,715,716],{"class":181,"line":309},[179,717,718],{},"print(lisB) # ['C', 'D']\n",[17,720,721],{},"Grab everything from index 3 onward:",[170,723,725],{"className":172,"code":724,"language":174,"meta":175,"style":175},"lisA = ['A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E', 'F']\nlisB = lisA[3:]\nprint(lisA) # ['A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E', 'F']\nprint(lisB) # ['C', 'D', 'F']\n",[34,726,727,731,736,740],{"__ignoreMap":175},[179,728,729],{"class":181,"line":182},[179,730,678],{},[179,732,733],{"class":181,"line":188},[179,734,735],{},"lisB = lisA[3:]\n",[179,737,738],{"class":181,"line":194},[179,739,319],{},[179,741,742],{"class":181,"line":309},[179,743,744],{},"print(lisB) # ['C', 'D', 'F']\n",[159,746,747],{"id":747},"copy",[17,749,750,751,753],{},"The ",[34,752,747],{}," method is exactly what it sounds like — it copies:",[170,755,757],{"className":172,"code":756,"language":174,"meta":175,"style":175},"lisA = [14, 30, 35, 42, 5, 16, 70, 98, 19, 100]\nlisB = lisA.copy()\nprint(id(lisA)) # 4464143936\nprint(id(lisB)) # 4464824640\n",[34,758,759,763,768,772],{"__ignoreMap":175},[179,760,761],{"class":181,"line":182},[179,762,616],{},[179,764,765],{"class":181,"line":188},[179,766,767],{},"lisB = lisA.copy()\n",[179,769,770],{"class":181,"line":194},[179,771,626],{},[179,773,774],{"class":181,"line":309},[179,775,631],{},[159,777,121],{"id":121},[17,779,780,782,783,785],{},[34,781,121],{}," actually works a lot like the ",[34,784,121],{}," syntax we write in JavaScript — you can use it to f